Options A and B are contradictory, and option D is unlikely as testosterone is not typically increased in menopause or premature ovarian failure.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. FSH levels are elevated, indicating ovarian failure or menopause. As a result, estrogen levels decrease which leads to decreased negative feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary gland, leading to increased LH levels. Therefore, option (C) is the correct answer. Increased serum estradiol and decreased serum LH as in option (A) would indicate estrogen-producing tumors or ovarian hyperstimulation. Increased serum progesterone and increased serum LH as in option (B) would indicate luteal phase defects or pregnancy. Decreased serum progesterone and increased serum testosterone as in option (D) would indicate polycystic ovarian syndrome.
